WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:02.360
All right.

00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:04.480
So, as Eric mentioned,

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:07.840
I want to talk about some deep learning work

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:08.760
that is not mine.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:11.680
If you're interested in the slides,

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:13.320
there's links to papers and things in here.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:17.920
So on GitHub, just go to Pepo and it's 2025Rforma.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:22.719
All right, so I want to talk about TabPFN.

00:00:22.719 --> 00:00:25.480
It's a deep learning model that could be used

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:27.260
for what they call tabular data.

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:28.920
It can do regression or classification

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:31.139
or density estimation.

00:00:31.139 --> 00:00:35.419
TabPFN stands for Tabular Prior Dated Fitted Network.

00:00:35.419 --> 00:00:39.380
And this tabular term in deep learning,

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:41.220
for like the last, I don't know, 20 years,

00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:43.099
deep learning has been much more concerned

00:00:43.099 --> 00:00:48.099
with image prediction, video, text,

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:49.900
and unstructured data.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:51.480
And so from their terminology,

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:54.700
tabular data is probably the data we've lived with forever,

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:56.240
which is a rectangular data set

00:00:56.240 --> 00:00:58.340
where you have columns and rows

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:01.200
and the columns are attributes of some characteristic

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:03.900
like predictors and outcomes and the rows are samples.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:07.800
So there's two main references.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:11.500
This first one, so there's two versions of the model,

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:13.099
at least in terms of software.

00:01:13.099 --> 00:01:16.919
So the first reference there in 2022 is the original one.

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:20.480
And then I'll mostly be describing version two

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:22.720
where the paper came out this year.

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:24.699
I don't know there's a lot difference from it

00:01:24.699 --> 00:01:27.480
in terms of methodology, but the model is,

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:29.559
as you'll see in a minute, more complex.

00:01:30.739 --> 00:01:33.540
Now, why would you wanna know about this?

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:35.339
Deep learning has not been successful

00:01:35.339 --> 00:01:38.419
with rectangular data sets.

00:01:38.419 --> 00:01:42.440
It's not often that they can create very large models

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:46.260
with millions of parameters that are often

00:01:48.639 --> 00:01:52.099
do worse than like a busa tree or random forest.

00:01:52.099 --> 00:01:56.699
And so this model actually seems to live up to the hype

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:59.519
to some degree, and I'm a very skeptical person,

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:01.320
especially when I first read this

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.320
like click baitish Gawker headline about like,

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:06.639
we do everything in seconds.

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:08.720
But I think actually they do kind of do that.

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:11.399
So let me walk you through, it's very unconventional

00:02:11.399 --> 00:02:13.600
and it's somewhat complicated

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:15.240
to describe how this thing works.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:18.399
So the main, there's a couple of main attributes

00:02:18.399 --> 00:02:19.320
of these models.

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:21.479
The first one is this notion of a data prior.

00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:23.800
So these authors wrote an earlier paper

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:25.479
where they showed that they could take

00:02:25.479 --> 00:02:27.820
a very large deep learning model

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:31.460
and comparing it to known benchmarks

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:34.380
actually do something that very well approximates

00:02:34.380 --> 00:02:35.880
Bayesian inference, right?

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:37.940
So we think about Bayesian models having a prior

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:40.940
and some data that produces a posterior probability

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:42.619
or posterior distribution.

00:02:42.619 --> 00:02:45.660
And they found that with a sufficiently large type

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:48.000
of deep learning model, they can do well,

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:53.119
they can basically do the same thing within like an epsilon.

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:55.860
The really interesting thing is when you think

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:58.179
about Bayesian analysis, like let's say we're trying

00:02:58.179 --> 00:03:01.179
to like model a single proportion.

00:03:01.179 --> 00:03:04.220
Our prior is on some singular scalar parameter,

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:06.479
like the probability of a coin being heads

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:07.619
or something like that.

00:03:07.619 --> 00:03:12.020
In this particular case, the prior is indexed by data sets.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:14.179
And so when we think about what the prior is,

00:03:14.179 --> 00:03:15.580
it's not like a scalar function,

00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:18.100
it's like this artificial notion of a data set

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:20.380
or this abstract notion of a data set.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:21.740
And so what they did is they developed

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:23.199
this like really complicated,

00:03:23.199 --> 00:03:26.399
and we don't know all the details of this part,

00:03:26.399 --> 00:03:30.240
but they've developed a very complicated like causal graph

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:34.240
that mimics like common data generating mechanisms

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:35.759
that we would see in rectangular data.

00:03:35.759 --> 00:03:37.919
And I'll show you a list in just a minute,

00:03:37.919 --> 00:03:39.960
but basically they have like a simulation system

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:41.679
that can generate data sets with different number

00:03:41.679 --> 00:03:43.679
of columns and different number of rows.

00:03:43.679 --> 00:03:46.520
And depending on how they set up the hyper parameters

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:49.199
for the prior, it could have like missing data

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:51.860
or like highly correlated predictors and things.

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:54.300
So when they talk about having a prior,

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:57.020
basically they can generate this probability,

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.820
this prior notion of what a data set would be

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:04.559
where data set is symbolized by the D here.

00:04:05.619 --> 00:04:07.179
And so we don't know again,

00:04:07.179 --> 00:04:09.699
all the nuances of this particular one,

00:04:09.699 --> 00:04:11.179
they mentioned a few aspects of it,

00:04:11.179 --> 00:04:13.220
but things that are probably in there

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:15.279
is like distributional effects.

00:04:15.279 --> 00:04:17.220
So when they simulate data from their prior,

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:18.540
it could be skewed data,

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:20.720
so they probably have some parameter governing that,

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:23.359
correlation structures between columns,

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:28.079
zero correlations maybe between rows and things like that.

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:29.000
In their causal graph,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.600
they can with some probability generate like missing data

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:35.420
based on some mechanism and so on.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:38.700
You can imagine there being part of that network

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:42.119
that handles like latent variables.

00:04:42.119 --> 00:04:43.359
So like in chemistry,

00:04:43.359 --> 00:04:45.239
when I used to work in computational chemistry,

00:04:45.239 --> 00:04:46.600
almost everything that we would do

00:04:46.619 --> 00:04:49.059
is based on size and charge of the molecule.

00:04:49.059 --> 00:04:51.179
And so you might have like 12 predictors

00:04:51.179 --> 00:04:53.559
that are actually driven by like a few handfuls

00:04:53.559 --> 00:04:54.820
of latent variables.

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:55.859
And that's probably something

00:04:55.859 --> 00:04:57.820
that they simulate in their data.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:59.179
And then lastly, one thing they do,

00:04:59.179 --> 00:05:00.779
and they call this the task,

00:05:00.779 --> 00:05:04.899
is they generate some simulated equation

00:05:04.899 --> 00:05:07.059
that relates the predictors to the outcome,

00:05:07.059 --> 00:05:10.779
and then simulate the parameters of that relationship

00:05:10.779 --> 00:05:12.519
and add some random error to it.

00:05:12.519 --> 00:05:14.540
So at the end of this simulation system,

00:05:14.559 --> 00:05:18.200
you basically get a data set that's artificial,

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:20.019
and it has some task,

00:05:20.019 --> 00:05:22.880
which is like a classification problem or regression problem

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:26.040
with different coefficients and functional forms.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:28.760
And so when they build their models,

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:29.839
as you'll see in a minute,

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:34.519
what they do is they generate quite a lot of these data sets

00:05:34.519 --> 00:05:37.760
and that's what they build their deep learning model on.

00:05:38.839 --> 00:05:40.079
So a little bit of math here,

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:42.220
what they basically have is,

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:45.160
if X and Y are the actual data that we have,

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.459
or the data we wanna predict, like an X,

00:05:47.459 --> 00:05:49.200
what they have is a simulation system

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:52.440
that generates a ton of these data sets and tasks.

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:54.279
And they basically have their deep learning model

00:05:54.279 --> 00:05:56.760
that approximates what Bayes' rule would do,

00:05:56.760 --> 00:05:59.040
which is like factoring together like the likelihood

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:01.579
and the prior, normalizing that,

00:06:01.579 --> 00:06:04.640
and then produces a posterior distribution, right?

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:06.440
And so this is just like a really fancy way

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:07.480
of writing Bayes' rule

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:09.959
in the context of their deep learning system.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:13.220
Now, the important thing is you just have X and Y,

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:15.100
you never really see the data sets

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:19.540
that were in the model and the task that they simulated.

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:21.880
Now, for version one of the model,

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:24.500
they used, I think about 500 data sets.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:25.320
With version two,

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:27.940
they scaled it up to 130 million realizations

00:06:27.940 --> 00:06:29.859
of the data set and the task.

00:06:29.859 --> 00:06:32.260
So they quite like scaled up the system.

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:35.540
And one really interesting thing about this model is,

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:38.019
the Python and R libraries for this,

00:06:38.019 --> 00:06:39.459
the model is already fit.

00:06:39.459 --> 00:06:41.799
So all the weights and everything are already estimated

00:06:41.799 --> 00:06:44.920
by the time the software is given to us.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:48.920
And we don't actually do any more estimation after that.

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:50.640
And so when we come in with our training set

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:52.399
and our samples that we wanna predict,

00:06:52.399 --> 00:06:54.440
we're not updating the network,

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:57.119
like using forward pass or back propagation

00:06:57.119 --> 00:06:58.480
to change the weights.

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:00.679
We do actually no additional estimation

00:07:00.679 --> 00:07:02.940
based on the actual data that we have

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:04.359
to get good predictions.

00:07:04.359 --> 00:07:06.359
And let's talk about how that works,

00:07:06.359 --> 00:07:08.579
because that's kind of a different thing.

00:07:10.459 --> 00:07:12.700
So if you've read anything about like neural networks

00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:14.440
or deep learning, like in the last 10 years,

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:17.519
probably the one word you may have heard of is attention.

00:07:17.519 --> 00:07:18.920
And so there's a really famous paper

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:21.559
called attention is all you need.

00:07:21.559 --> 00:07:23.700
And these people came up with a mechanism

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:27.100
to really greatly improve how these models work.

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:29.380
And I think it's not unreasonable to say

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:31.959
most of the advances we've had in LLMs

00:07:31.959 --> 00:07:34.799
and other complicated like sentence prediction models

00:07:34.799 --> 00:07:37.239
and things like that are largely in terms of,

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:40.100
or due to these things called attention mechanisms.

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:41.500
And so the way it works is, again,

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:44.260
remember we have a tabular data set.

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.739
The TabPFN people do two types of attention.

00:07:46.739 --> 00:07:48.980
They do what they call feature attention,

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:51.739
which basically allows the model to relate

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:58.420
between column, let's say between predictor relationships,

00:07:58.459 --> 00:08:00.660
such as like interactions or things like that.

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:04.140
And then they also allow to look across the rows at once

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:06.239
so you can get like relationships

00:08:06.239 --> 00:08:09.679
between different rows of a particular column.

00:08:09.679 --> 00:08:11.559
So you can imagine the feature attention

00:08:11.559 --> 00:08:13.299
being really good at things like, I don't know,

00:08:13.299 --> 00:08:15.720
like spline terms, you know, implicitly

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:17.959
or interaction effects and things like that.

00:08:17.959 --> 00:08:21.059
Whereas the sample attention might do really well

00:08:21.059 --> 00:08:23.760
at like serial correlation, things like that.

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.760
And so in their network, they have the ability

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:29.399
to really estimate these relationships in either dimension.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:32.400
And from that model, once you push your data through,

00:08:32.419 --> 00:08:35.140
you basically get some posterior distribution

00:08:35.140 --> 00:08:36.739
that's symbolized here.

00:08:36.739 --> 00:08:39.539
Now, one of the interesting things is, like I said,

00:08:39.539 --> 00:08:41.520
there's no actual estimation.

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.580
In fact, the training set isn't really a training set

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:45.460
because you're not estimating anything from it.

00:08:45.460 --> 00:08:47.419
So the way their model works is you take the data

00:08:47.419 --> 00:08:49.099
that you have, which we would normally think of

00:08:49.099 --> 00:08:51.619
as a training set, and you concatenate the data

00:08:51.619 --> 00:08:53.260
you want to predict to the bottom of that,

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:54.859
like shown here.

00:08:54.859 --> 00:08:58.419
And what they do is they push this data set,

00:08:58.419 --> 00:09:00.859
the entirety of it, through the network at once.

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:03.799
So you need both the training set and the test samples

00:09:03.799 --> 00:09:05.700
or the unknown samples to make a prediction

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:07.640
on the unknown samples.

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:10.320
And the way that works is through the intention mechanism.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:13.200
And so what it actually does is it doesn't really do

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:16.799
like a pure similarity search like we would think of it,

00:09:16.799 --> 00:09:18.640
but it basically has a weighting mechanism

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:21.200
that can look for weights in the model,

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:24.280
the parameters of the neural network of the model

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:26.239
that are most relevant for the samples

00:09:26.239 --> 00:09:27.400
that you're trying to predict.

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:29.520
So as you start to push the training set through the model,

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:31.820
it's doing what they call in-context learning,

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:34.059
and it's kind of getting an idea of like what part

00:09:34.059 --> 00:09:36.940
of this really huge neural network is relevant

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.140
to the type of data that I want to predict.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:42.080
And so what it does is it generates a set of weights

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:44.820
that upweights model parameters in the neural network

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:46.940
that are relevant to the data that you have at hand

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:49.179
that you just gave it, and downweights things

00:09:49.179 --> 00:09:50.859
that are more irrelevant.

00:09:50.859 --> 00:09:52.020
So, you know, let's say you have

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:54.020
completely uncorrelated predictors,

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:56.179
it would downweight the part of that neural network

00:09:56.200 --> 00:10:00.159
that handles like latent factors like PCA type effects.

00:10:00.159 --> 00:10:02.719
And so in Accents, the training set,

00:10:02.719 --> 00:10:04.619
it just like primes the pump

00:10:04.619 --> 00:10:06.000
for what the model should be doing.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.159
So by the time that the new samples you want to predict

00:10:09.159 --> 00:10:12.280
are pushed to the network, it's relatively localized

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:15.159
the parts of the larger model that will be relevant

00:10:15.159 --> 00:10:16.960
for the samples you want to predict.

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:23.599
Like I said, version two is trained on 130 million data sets

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:25.400
of different sizes.

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:27.739
It's intended use for what they think of as small data set

00:10:27.739 --> 00:10:29.460
from the deep learning perspective.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:31.219
And they consider that to be, you know,

00:10:31.219 --> 00:10:33.900
a training set up to 10,000 samples,

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:36.140
500 features and 10 classes.

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:41.140
And you can do more than 10,000 samples or 500 features.

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:43.380
The maximum of 10 classes is sort of baked

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:45.140
into the algorithm right now.

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:47.140
And as you'll see in a minute that I don't know

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:50.179
that we need up to 10,000 training set samples,

00:10:50.179 --> 00:10:51.739
but it depends on your data,

00:10:51.739 --> 00:10:54.539
but I'll show you some simulations in a minute.

00:10:54.559 --> 00:10:56.840
And I don't have any fancy plot to show you,

00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:59.320
but I probably applied this to about a dozen data sets

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:02.760
that I have, and it always ranks in the top five.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:06.039
So it's doing very, very well performance wise

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:08.119
compared to other models.

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:09.719
So from a predictor performance,

00:11:09.719 --> 00:11:11.320
it's very, very, very effective.

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:15.359
Now, one thing to keep in mind is if you're like me

00:11:15.359 --> 00:11:18.119
and you've lived in this tabular world your whole life,

00:11:18.119 --> 00:11:20.039
you know, the notion of needing what I think of

00:11:20.039 --> 00:11:21.840
as like specialized hardware to make a prediction

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:23.559
is a little bit odd.

00:11:23.559 --> 00:11:25.780
But basically a GPU is required.

00:11:25.780 --> 00:11:28.460
You can do the calculations on the CPU,

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:31.260
but it uses an inordinate amount of memory

00:11:31.260 --> 00:11:33.820
and it takes quite a long time to compute.

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:37.219
Whereas with a basic GPU, nothing extravagant,

00:11:37.219 --> 00:11:39.380
you can basically get a lot of predictions in a second,

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:40.320
like they say.

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:44.260
So really, if you have what's called a CUDA based GPU,

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:46.659
which is like an NVIDIA card,

00:11:46.659 --> 00:11:48.500
your prediction time is very fast.

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:51.619
Otherwise you're gonna be waiting a long time.

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:54.080
Like I have a Mac right now, a Mac desktop

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:56.719
that has like a fancy GPU with like 24 cores,

00:11:56.719 --> 00:11:58.799
but it doesn't use CUDA instructions.

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:01.400
So it's kind of useless to me for this type of model.

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:04.280
You really need like a CUDA based graphics card,

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:06.520
which tend to be like an NVIDIA type card.

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:08.359
That might seem odd.

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:10.760
Like if you're coming from a background like mine,

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:12.719
where I've never needed like special hardware

00:12:12.719 --> 00:12:14.599
to make predictions on a couple of samples.

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:17.559
But in this particular case, that's really what's required.

00:12:18.719 --> 00:12:20.520
A quick question I'll answer real quick

00:12:20.539 --> 00:12:23.479
is pre-processing, feature engineering.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:27.700
Technically, no, it does a lot for you.

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:30.500
I usually, when I've tested this, I've given it as is.

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:32.299
You don't have to convert to dummy variables

00:12:32.299 --> 00:12:34.979
or transformations.

00:12:34.979 --> 00:12:37.020
That is all handled inside the network.

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:43.219
So I've been sort of studying this sort of indirectly

00:12:43.219 --> 00:12:44.940
because we don't have a lot of,

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:46.760
we're not like obfuscating information,

00:12:46.760 --> 00:12:49.780
but there's a lot that is in papers,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:51.239
but not in software.

00:12:52.159 --> 00:12:53.880
And so one thing that I always think about

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:55.799
when we look at new models is,

00:12:55.799 --> 00:12:58.200
well, what if I have a lot of predictors in my training set

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:00.239
that have nothing to do with the outcome?

00:13:00.239 --> 00:13:01.799
And so I have the simulation I've been running

00:13:01.799 --> 00:13:04.960
for like 10 years now for like different books

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:09.599
and look at, for a particular simulation that I like,

00:13:09.599 --> 00:13:11.359
fit models of different types

00:13:11.359 --> 00:13:13.799
when you take and add irrelevant predictors.

00:13:13.799 --> 00:13:16.960
So the X's axis here is how many noise predictors we have.

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:19.179
The right, or the Y axis here

00:13:19.179 --> 00:13:21.260
is basically the inflation in the error.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:23.260
So you want this to stay flat.

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:25.700
And if you look at something like GleamNet,

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:26.599
it doesn't really matter

00:13:26.599 --> 00:13:28.539
how many extra predictors you put in.

00:13:28.539 --> 00:13:30.719
Some of them might be included periodically,

00:13:30.719 --> 00:13:33.380
but the performance doesn't get markedly worse.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:34.619
And then a counter example

00:13:34.619 --> 00:13:36.940
is basic feed-forward neural networks.

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:38.659
As you add more noise predictors,

00:13:38.659 --> 00:13:41.299
you really, really degrade the root mean squared error

00:13:41.299 --> 00:13:42.580
and the error gets a lot worse.

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:44.739
And KNN's are really awful at this.

00:13:44.739 --> 00:13:46.119
And these methods in black

00:13:46.119 --> 00:13:49.119
don't have any real mechanism for feature selection,

00:13:49.119 --> 00:13:52.719
but methods like Cubist or Mars or something like that do,

00:13:52.719 --> 00:13:54.799
and they tend to be very resistant.

00:13:54.799 --> 00:13:55.919
And then when you come down here,

00:13:55.919 --> 00:13:58.359
we don't really know what TabPFN does,

00:13:58.359 --> 00:13:59.760
if it does anything at all,

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:02.039
but for some reason it's incredibly flat

00:14:02.039 --> 00:14:04.840
when it comes to irrelevant predictors.

00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:07.400
It seems to do a really good job of knowing

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:11.799
that it should not let these noise features interfere.

00:14:12.679 --> 00:14:14.400
I'm not gonna talk about this model too much,

00:14:15.059 --> 00:14:16.219
but this is a more conventional

00:14:16.219 --> 00:14:18.179
tabular neural network model,

00:14:18.179 --> 00:14:21.580
and ironically is designed to deal with irrelevant features.

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:24.099
It has an architecture that will downweight features

00:14:24.099 --> 00:14:26.380
and it actually does kind of poorly

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:29.500
when you have a lot of predictors that are irrelevant.

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:31.119
And so we don't know why,

00:14:31.119 --> 00:14:34.659
but TabPFN seems to be resistant to this

00:14:34.659 --> 00:14:36.900
or do some sort of automatic feature selection,

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:38.859
whether they do it explicitly or implicitly,

00:14:38.859 --> 00:14:40.580
it's handling this pretty well.

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:42.960
Now, one other question is,

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:47.119
I talked about attention and upweighting model parameters.

00:14:47.119 --> 00:14:48.280
And so one question I had is,

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:50.320
well, will that happen after 10 data points

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:51.479
or a thousand data points,

00:14:51.479 --> 00:14:54.359
or what do we need to do the right thing here?

00:14:55.239 --> 00:14:56.700
And so I took a real data set

00:14:56.700 --> 00:14:59.119
that has about a 4,800 training set samples

00:14:59.119 --> 00:15:01.719
and about 1,300, it's a test set,

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:03.280
but we'll just call it a holdout.

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:06.840
And then I just randomly sampled training set rows

00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:09.239
and then predicted this holdout set.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:12.260
And so what I found is in the X-axis here is in log units

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:15.299
in terms of the training set number of rows,

00:15:15.299 --> 00:15:17.700
that if you only have like four rows,

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:20.859
your performance is really awful

00:15:20.859 --> 00:15:24.140
and is to be expected as we increase the number of rows,

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:25.780
we get down to like a hundred,

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:27.539
we're actually getting decent performance.

00:15:27.539 --> 00:15:28.820
And then we get to about a thousand

00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:30.979
for this particular data set.

00:15:30.979 --> 00:15:33.179
We've really stabilized our predictions

00:15:33.179 --> 00:15:35.900
and are getting very good performance.

00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:37.460
That's true for the Briar score.

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:40.900
You can see the air into the RC curve gets pretty high,

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:42.159
you know, after a certain degree,

00:15:42.159 --> 00:15:44.059
like 500 or a thousand samples.

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:46.719
Now the prediction time actually,

00:15:46.719 --> 00:15:48.599
this is done on a GPU,

00:15:48.599 --> 00:15:51.080
actually does increase exponentially,

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:53.799
but again, it's two seconds

00:15:53.799 --> 00:15:56.880
for predicting about 1,300 samples.

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:58.799
So even though it's getting larger,

00:15:58.799 --> 00:16:00.679
this prediction time with the right hardware

00:16:00.679 --> 00:16:03.020
is not really that much of an obstacle.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:06.200
To support this, you can,

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:09.140
I just randomly selected like 12 data points

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:11.179
and looked at their class probability estimates

00:16:11.179 --> 00:16:12.940
as the classification problem

00:16:12.940 --> 00:16:14.500
to see how well they converged.

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:16.179
And here's one that in the end

00:16:16.179 --> 00:16:19.719
has a very low probability of being the event,

00:16:19.719 --> 00:16:21.919
but you can see on the initial data set

00:16:21.919 --> 00:16:24.419
with like four rows sampled at random,

00:16:24.419 --> 00:16:27.020
almost every row here is showing something

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:29.239
like 50% class probability.

00:16:29.239 --> 00:16:31.219
And like this, when many of them do converge,

00:16:31.219 --> 00:16:33.419
you can see this last one does converge.

00:16:33.419 --> 00:16:35.919
I'm not sure what this jump is around the middle,

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:38.640
but then you do have one or two

00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:41.200
that still have a high degree of uncertainty

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:43.520
over the training set size.

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:44.359
And that's just probably

00:16:44.359 --> 00:16:46.159
because they're difficult to predict.

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:50.200
So we don't know that we need 10,000 data points

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:51.799
for a lot of data sets,

00:16:51.799 --> 00:16:53.400
depends on their complexity,

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:55.000
but we certainly do need, you know,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.640
more than a handful to sort of get attention

00:16:57.640 --> 00:16:59.140
working the way we want it to.

00:17:00.119 --> 00:17:01.880
Now, there is a lot more that we could talk about.

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:03.000
I don't have time,

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:05.260
but if you look at the link to the second paper,

00:17:05.260 --> 00:17:07.819
they do a lot about talking about actual inference,

00:17:07.819 --> 00:17:10.020
meaning like the machine learning people,

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:12.239
which I sometimes consider myself,

00:17:12.239 --> 00:17:13.420
but when you read about them

00:17:13.420 --> 00:17:15.119
or hear them talk about doing inference,

00:17:15.119 --> 00:17:17.380
they really are saying prediction.

00:17:17.380 --> 00:17:20.140
I mean here getting like posterior probabilities

00:17:20.140 --> 00:17:21.900
for predictions or, you know,

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:24.459
predictive intervals and things like that.

00:17:24.459 --> 00:17:25.300
That's easy to do

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:28.500
because they approximate a posterior distribution.

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:30.300
You can also ensemble this model

00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:32.300
and that seems to be effective.

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:34.520
They have their own internal variable importance measurement

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:36.439
and finally they do,

00:17:36.439 --> 00:17:39.880
you can use regular like explainability measures,

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:44.839
but they have a built-in Shapley API.

00:17:44.839 --> 00:17:45.680
So if you want to,

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:48.040
if you like those particular model methods,

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:50.800
you can get them from this model pretty easily.

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:52.800
And then finally, there's a Python library

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:57.280
and I think somebody has posted the link to the R port.

00:17:57.280 --> 00:17:58.319
The code is very similar.

00:17:58.319 --> 00:18:00.359
It's basically what you would expect.

00:18:00.359 --> 00:18:02.619
You load your library in Python,

00:18:02.619 --> 00:18:05.459
you initialize the classifier or the regressor,

00:18:05.459 --> 00:18:08.300
give it the training set and then make predictions.

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:09.699
It's the same thing here.

00:18:09.699 --> 00:18:11.939
Nothing really happens, you know, at this point.

00:18:11.939 --> 00:18:14.020
I think all it does is like embed the data,

00:18:14.020 --> 00:18:16.780
but it's just waiting to concatenate these data

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:18.680
with whatever data is in the test set.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:23.020
It is kind of being incorporated into tiny models.

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:26.020
One problem that we have,

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:27.500
and this is really a Python problem,

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:30.140
is we use reticulate here.

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:34.239
This is awful, but if you load any R package

00:18:34.239 --> 00:18:38.000
that uses OpenMP and then be a reticulate

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.040
load a Python package,

00:18:40.040 --> 00:18:42.800
if that Python package uses OpenMP,

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:43.920
as soon as you invoke it,

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:46.280
like running a function, it segfaults.

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:49.359
And that is a known problem with Python.

00:18:49.359 --> 00:18:51.839
So that's the main thing for me,

00:18:51.839 --> 00:18:53.280
fully integrating with tiny models

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:55.599
is if you don't read the fine print

00:18:55.599 --> 00:18:58.040
and initialize your Python library first,

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:00.579
you're gonna get like a bunch of segfaults.

00:19:00.579 --> 00:19:02.060
So we're working on that,

00:19:02.060 --> 00:19:07.060
but yes, it will have broader usage in tiny models.

00:19:08.859 --> 00:19:10.180
And that's pretty much it.

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:12.459
Again, thank you to everybody for the attention

00:19:12.459 --> 00:19:14.540
or for the invitation to speak.

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:18.380
And thanks to Simon, Daniel, and Tomas at Posit

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:20.979
who helped with various aspects of this presentation.

00:19:22.300 --> 00:19:23.900
Thank you so much, Max.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:27.280
That was very, very informative.

00:19:28.180 --> 00:19:31.560
I guess one question that did come in was,

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:34.380
is there actually a limit on the size

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:38.180
or number of say rows or columns of a tabular dataset

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:42.300
that your TabPF in order for it to handle effectively?

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:44.939
Is there kind of a limitation on that?

00:19:44.939 --> 00:19:48.599
They have limitations built into the software,

00:19:48.599 --> 00:19:51.260
but they also have an option to ignore those.

00:19:51.260 --> 00:19:54.339
So I think it's 10,000 rows in the training set

00:19:54.339 --> 00:19:57.339
and 500 columns.

00:19:57.359 --> 00:19:59.000
I don't know that we need all,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.640
I mean, it depends on how difficult your problem is.

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:03.959
I don't know that we need 10,000,

00:20:03.959 --> 00:20:06.680
but I did test it on a spectroscopy dataset

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:10.560
that I have that had about 600 predictors.

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:11.839
And I just turned the switch off

00:20:11.839 --> 00:20:14.239
that says ignore the limitations.

00:20:14.239 --> 00:20:15.479
And it still did pretty well.

00:20:15.479 --> 00:20:18.040
I'm not sure what it does in that instance,

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:21.900
but you can get around those if you want to.

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:23.699
You'd have to probably play around a little bit

00:20:23.699 --> 00:20:25.719
to see for your dataset,

00:20:25.719 --> 00:20:28.920
like how much of that training set you need.

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:33.119
But again, with the GPU, you get pretty fast predictions.

00:20:33.119 --> 00:20:35.280
So it may not be that big of a deal

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:37.420
if you have like 20,000, I don't know.

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:40.640
But that's something to look at, yeah.

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:41.479
So, okay.

00:20:41.479 --> 00:20:43.479
So speaking of speed then,

00:20:43.479 --> 00:20:47.199
so do you feel like the training time with the TabPF

00:20:47.199 --> 00:20:50.699
and maybe compared to maybe more traditional models

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:52.920
is it like quite a bit faster

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:54.599
or is there a certain percentage faster

00:20:54.599 --> 00:20:57.260
or like did you guys, something you measured?

00:20:58.280 --> 00:21:00.800
I did, but it's hard to say

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:02.119
because there's really no training time.

00:21:02.119 --> 00:21:04.479
It doesn't actually estimate, right?

00:21:04.479 --> 00:21:09.400
So what I did, and I'm gonna reproduce this on a GPU.

00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:11.180
It's kind of on this slide.

00:21:11.180 --> 00:21:14.000
I did look to see what the total time

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:17.719
from getting your data into the system

00:21:17.719 --> 00:21:22.319
and getting the final prediction over this size.

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:27.680
So if I, I'm predicting 1300 samples in two seconds

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:30.420
when I have a training set, that's about 5,000.

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:33.520
So per sample, that's pretty quick.

00:21:33.520 --> 00:21:36.420
So I can imagine that going more exponential

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:37.900
like further up this curve

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:42.900
as you have like a wider training set or more rows

00:21:42.939 --> 00:21:45.439
but I can't imagine it's gonna be minutes.

00:21:45.459 --> 00:21:49.339
So I would suspect it's fairly competitive

00:21:49.339 --> 00:21:50.859
in terms of time.

00:21:50.859 --> 00:21:53.099
And there are some things you can tune

00:21:53.099 --> 00:21:56.140
but I can't imagine that, much like random forest

00:21:56.140 --> 00:21:59.060
like the default seem to work pretty well.

00:21:59.060 --> 00:22:01.579
It's possible you can get a little bit more performance

00:22:01.579 --> 00:22:02.920
by tuning these.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:05.300
But again, I'm not sure what the notion

00:22:05.300 --> 00:22:06.579
of like resampling is here

00:22:06.579 --> 00:22:08.619
because it's not really estimating anything.

00:22:08.619 --> 00:22:11.819
So these are like really weird and interesting problems

00:22:11.819 --> 00:22:13.859
for this particular model to figure out.

